    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-11-22T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-11-22T07:00:00-05:00" n="816"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d816">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">867N.01/1299: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Jerusalem</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Wadsworth</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jerusalem</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-11-22T14:00:00+02:00"
                            >November 22, 1938—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received November 22—12:48 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>While local British circles generally maintain the view reported in the
                    penultimate paragraph of my telegram of November 12, 4 p.m. and believe their
                    Government’s projected new Palestine policy will include provisions drastically
                    limiting future Jewish immigration, recognizing such limitation to be a <hi
                        rend="italic">sine qua non</hi> to Arab acquiescence, I find a growing
                    conviction that announcement of any such policy seemed to be precluded for the
                    time being by public reaction in England and the United States to the last
                    fortnight’s Jewish persecutions in Germany and must await either a considerable
                    abatement of that reaction or comprehensive plan for the settlement elsewhere
                    than in Palestine of German Jewish refugees.</p>
                <p>Information received from local Arab sources while not fully convincing tends to
                    confirm Palmer’s telegram of November 11, noon, regarding the attitude of the
                    Mufti.</p>
                <p>As the Consulate General’s annual allotment of $700 for telegrams has already
                    been overspent by approximately $800 I should appreciate an increase of
                    $2000.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wadsworth</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
